<DESCRIPT>  PAST; MULTIPLE; MURDER; SAN-FRANCISCO; PRISON; TIME; RULING  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Two Black Muslims serving life prison terms for the racially motivated "Zebra"
killings that terrorized San Francisco in 1973-74 were denied parole and
cannot reapply for three years.;    On Tuesday, a three-member panel of the
state Board of Prison Terms rejected petitions for parole by Manuel Moore and
Jessie Lee Cooks, both 46, said board spokeswoman Phyllis Scott.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  'ZEBRA' KILLERS LOSE PAROLE BIDS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Sixteen assault victims and relatives and supporters of murder victims
attended Tuesday's hearings. Scott said seven spoke against parole for Moore
and three made statements against releasing Cooks.;    Fourteen white people
were killed and eight others injured during the series of attacks that
panicked San Francisco residents during the winter of 1973-74. The victims
were shot, stabbed and, in the case of one woman, beheaded with a machete.;   
The slayings were dubbed the "Zebra" killings because police used a separate
Z, or Zebra, radio band during their investigation of the slayings.  </TEXT>
